{"title": "Update on Spirulina | NutritionFacts.org", "author": "Dr Michael Greger", "url": "https://nutritionfacts.org/es/video/update-on-spirulina/", "hostname": "nutritionfacts.org", "description": "Concerns about spirulina supplements extend to liver toxicity.", "sitename": "NutritionFacts.org", "date": "2009-09-29", "id": null, "license": null, "body": null, "comments": "", "commentsbody": null, "raw_text": null, "text": "What about the microscopic greens, like spirulina? Of all the controversial findings I\u2019ve shared from the medical literature over the years, this is the one I get the most mail about. People love their pond scum.\nSo, I\u2019ve stayed on top of the literature, and it\u2019s time for an update. There\u2019s no doubt that spirulina does some amazing things, but as with everything in life, it\u2019s all about risk/benefit. And so, although in 2007, the data pointed against spirulina, and I threw mine out and encouraged others to do the same, is it possible that the balance of evidence has shifted back in favor? Still harmful? Half and half? Or, crept back to helpful?\nIn 2007, I was concerned about spirulina because of muscle breakdown, and these new findings have me concerned about liver cancer, too. 94% of samples were found to be contaminated with hepatotoxic microcystin toxins.\nTo see any graphs, charts, graphics, images, and quotes to which Dr. Greger may be referring, watch the above video. This is just an approximation of the audio contributed by veganmontreal.\nPlease consider\n[volunteering](https://nutritionfacts.org/volunteer) to help out on the site.", "language": null, "image": "https://nutritionfacts.org/app/themes/sage/dist/images/default-image.png", "pagetype": "video.other", "links": ["https://nutritionfacts.org/es/", "#", "https://nutritionfacts.org/video/update-on-spirulina/", "https://nutritionfacts.org/es/videos/", "https://nutritionfacts.org/es/video/la-leche-de-soja-para-los-sintomas-vaginales-de-la-menopausia/", "htt